510	[The candidate-inverse family equalizes the restricted legs (C2 transported)]
511	  \label{lem:gr_glueChartFamily_equalizes}
512	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.glueChartFamily_equalizes}
513	  \uses{def:gr_glueChartFamily, def:scheme_modules_glue, lem:gr_glueData_bridges,
514	    lem:modules_pullback_basechange_transport, lem:gr_overlap_appIso_compat,
515	    lem:gr_glueChartComponent_self_counit, lem:modules_restrictFunctorIsoPullback_mathlib}
516	  The family \cref{def:gr_glueChartFamily} equalizes the two restricted descent legs
517	  \(\iota_i^{*}a\) and \(\iota_i^{*}b\); equivalently, it lands in the restricted
518	  equalizer \(\iota_i^{*}\mathcal{M}\). This is the first descent obligation, where the
519	  triple-overlap multiplicativity (C2) of \cref{def:scheme_modules_glue} is consumed.
520	\end{lemma}
521	\begin{proof}
522	  \uses{def:gr_glueChartFamily, def:scheme_modules_glue, lem:gr_glueData_bridges,
523	    lem:modules_pullback_basechange_transport, lem:gr_overlap_appIso_compat,
524	    lem:gr_glueChartComponent_self_counit, lem:gr_glueOverlapFactor_mate}
525	  It suffices to check equality after projecting to each factor \((p,q)\) of the
526	  restricted overlap product, through the product-preservation comparison of
527	  \(\iota_i^{*}\) (the same comparison discipline as \cref{lem:gr_glueRestrict_proj_compat});
528	  the \((p,q)\)-component is the equation
529	  \[
530	    \mathrm{s}_i^{(p)}\ \circ\ \iota_i^{*}\bigl(a_{(p,q)}\bigr)
531	      \;=\;
532	    \mathrm{s}_i^{(q)}\ \circ\ \iota_i^{*}\bigl(b_{(p,q)}\bigr)
533	  \]
534	  between morphisms \(\mathcal{M}_i \to \iota_i^{*}\bigl((f_{pq}\circ \iota_p)_{*}
535	  f_{pq}^{*}\mathcal{M}_p\bigr)\). Transpose this equation along the open immersion
536	  \(q_{pq} : V_{ipq} \hookrightarrow U_i\) of the triple overlap \(V_{ipq} = V_{ip}
537	  \times_{U_i} V_{iq}\) (with \(q_{pq}\) the first projection followed by \(f_{ip}\)),
538	  exactly as the pair-level transpose of \cref{lem:gr_glueOverlapFactor_mate}. The
539	  transpose requires the triple-overlap analogues of the pair-level toolkit:
540	  \begin{enumerate}
541	    \item the opens identity \((f_{pq}\circ \iota_p)^{-1}(\iota_i(V)) =
542	      \tau\bigl(q_{pq}^{-1}(V)\bigr)\) on \(V_{ipq}\), where \(\tau\) is the base-change
543	      transport morphism, obtained from the pullback square, the cocycle-transport
544	      factorisation, and the gluing-incidence criterion exactly as the pair-level
545	      opens identity of \cref{lem:glueOverlapBaseChangeIso};
546	    \item a triple overlap base change \((f_{pq}\circ \iota_p)_{*}\circ \iota_i^{*}
547	      \cong \tau^{*}\circ (q_{pq})_{*}\), assembled by the same four-factor recipe
548	      (pushforward composition, transport of the opens functor, the congruence factor,
549	      and the inverse pushforward composition) over (1), with the section-level
550	      compatibility proved by the \(\mathrm{appLE}\)-calculus pattern of
551	      \cref{lem:gr_overlap_appIso_compat};
552	    \item with (1) and (2) in place, the transposed component equation \emph{is} the
553	      cocycle multiplicativity (C2) of \cref{def:scheme_modules_glue} at the triple
554	      \((i,p,q)\), conjugated by the base-change transports
555	      \cref{lem:modules_pullback_basechange_transport}; the geometric bridges
556	      \cref{lem:gr_glueData_bridges} were chosen so that the endpoints of the two sides
557	      line up on the nose.
558	  \end{enumerate}
559	  The degenerate pairs \(p = i\) or \(q = i\) instead invoke the self-identity (C1)
560	  through \cref{lem:gr_glueChartComponent_self_counit} and the congruence cast
561	  \cref{lem:gr_pullbackCongr_hom_eqToHom}.
562	\end{proof}
